convert: using spaces instead of tabs now

yes, we finally gave up being rebellious, and adapted
another pep8 guideline.

you may still use tabs transparently on your local machine,
git can automagically convert the spaces to tabs for your editing.

=> your files will have tabs, but git stores them as spaces.

in your local repo, create/edit .git/info/attributes:

	*.py  filter=tabspace

then configure the repository:

	git config --global filter.tabspace.smudge 'unexpand --tabs=4 --first-only'
	git config --global filter.tabspace.clean  'expand --tabs=4 --initial'

update all files in the local repo to have tabs instead of spaces:

	git checkout HEAD -- **

when you commit and push your code, the tabs will be saved as spaces.

Bug #5: Include guards became unique.

Some include guards did not fit to the expected naming convention of the
C++ language standard. This detail was fixed by the addition of a prefix.

The probability for name clashes was also reduced by the addition of a kind
of universally unique identifier as a suffix.

use $(MAKE) variable in main Makefile

Using special $(MAKE) variable has some benefits over explicitly calling
'make'.
When using this variable, make knows automatically to pass some of its
arguments to lower-level invocations.
Among other features, this enables multi-threaded building from top-dir.

game: Made shared_ptrs into unique_ptr and added an implementation of make_unique

Some objects that were represented in the engine were held in shared_ptrs,
despite having a single owner and a well-defined lifetime.
I moved them to unique_ptrs so that it was clear that they had a single owner,
and so that it was obvious when they were released.
I also added an implementation of make_unique from c++14 to facilitate the use of unique_ptrs

convert: fixes strings with garbage data past their \0 terminators

Real world case: empires2_x1.dat has a string b'M\x00\xf8\x004"\xf8\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00', which has a bunch of garbage after its terminator. data.decode('utf-8') trips up on this because \xf8 is not a valid unicode char.
This patch fixes `zstr` to truncate data to right before the first \0, or to keep it entirely if there is no \0, before utf8-decoding it.

PyInterface and some other minor changes

This commit completes the C++ <-> Python interface, including:

 - openage is now a shared library
 - moved `py/openage` -> `openage`
 - moved `py/openage/codecompliance` -> `buildsystem/codecompliance`
 - integrated Cython into buildsystem
 - C++ -> Py function calling
  - C++ API is specified in PXD annotations in `.h` files
  - cpp/pyinterface/pyfunc.h
   - Func<returntype, arg0type, arg1type, ...>
   - Callable objects
   - Designed to be filled with pointers to cdef functions
   - __don't use raw function pointers in the interface__
  - openage/cppinterface/setup.py
   - setup() Fills the PyFunc pointers
   - must be called before using libopenage functionality
 - Exception translation
  - cpp/pyinterface/exctranslate.h
   - translate_exc_cpp_to_py
   - translate_exc_py_to_cpp
  - py/cppinterface/exctranslate.py
   - describe_exception
   - raise_cpp_error
  - C++ functions that are declared 'except +' if they may throw
  - Python functions that are declared 'except *' if they may raise
  - GIL-safe
  - everything is translated back and forth
   - metadata
   - message
   - backtrace
 - Documentation

C++:

 - Overhauled exception code
  - now lives in `error/error.h`
  - exceptions automatically store their cause exception
  - exceptions can collect backtraces
  - see demo in `cpp/error/demo.cpp`
  - Hierarchies may now be used
  - `doc/implementation/exceptions`
 - Moved util/error.h to error/error
 - Added error/handlers.cpp, which provides a SIGSEGV and terminate handler
 - refactored LZXD code
  - removed many C-isms and micro-optimizations
  - simplified codeflow, split methods into smaller ones
  - file split into multiple smaller ones (`cpp/util/compress`)
  - `decompress` replaced by `decompress_frame`, which decompresses just
    32768 bytes at a time instead of everything at once.
  - exposed to Python using the PyInterface
 - Simplified C++ logging
  - ExternalStringStream: like stringstream, but appends to a custom buffer
 - Modernized C++ testing
  - now uses TestError (e.g. via the `TESTFAIL` macro) instead of return values.
 - C++ exceptions can collect backtraces
 - `SIGSEGV` and `std::terminate` handlers
 - Enum class that allows adding new members at runtime, and associated data.
  - used by `log::lvl`
 - `util/init.h`: `OnInit` and `OnDeInit`: to call functions on dynamic initialization
 - fixed a bug with Timer

Python:

 - Bumped Python version requirement to 3.4
 - Massive clean-up
  - Unified all utility modules into the openage.util package
  - Removed some code that got obsoleted in the process
  - Made stuff more pylint-compliant
  - Replaced home-brewn Enum and NamedObject implementations by enum.Enum
 - Implemented some utilities
  - openage/util/fslike.py
   - FileSystemLikeObject abstract base class
   - Directory FileSystemLikeObject
  - openage/util/filelike.py
   - FileLikeObject abstract base class
   - StreamSeekBuffer FileLikeObject
   - StreamFragment FileLikeObject
   - FIFO FileLikeObject
  - FSLikeObject used by convert and codegen
 - Overhauled testing system
  - openage.testing.testing.assert_result
  - openage.testing.testing.assert_raises
  - openage.testing.testing.TestError
  - now done without CTest
  - C++ and Python tests and demos all called via Python
 - Integrated cabextract/cab.py with the rest of the project
  - now a FileSystemLikeObject
  - takes a FileLikeObject as an argument
  - added tests
 - PEFile has been refactored
  - resource strings are now resolved
  - the code uses NamedStructs
 - The Python logger now forwards to the C++ logger if the interface has been
   initialized
  - Central management of current loglevel
   - `--verbose`, `--quiet`
 - Program has one single entry point: `openage.__main__.main()`
  - run with `python3 -m openage`
  - alternatively: `./run`
  - subcommands: `game`, `test`, `codegen`
 - Media file conversion is now done when launching the game.

Buildsystem:

 - added valgrind-python.supp, a valgrind suppression file.
 - added basic whitespace compliance checking for textfiles
 - added pylint code compliance checking
  - Many files are not yet pylint-compliant; those have a header
    '# TODO pylint: disable=C,R,whatever categories'
 - added selective code compliance checking (closes #229)
 - re-worked Makefile targets

fixes documentation issue #511

If a parent directory of openage contains a space, 'make doc' (or better, doxygen)
splits the absolute path from the INPUT tag in bin/Doxygen in two directorys.
That way, the necessary files cannot be found and no documentation is created.

This commit adds quotation marks to the responsible cmake file.

doc: Update DRS file format.

Internally, Age of Empires does something like this when reading files
from a DRS archive:

```c
read_drs_file('bina', 50500);
```

Note how it uses a C char with multiple bytes. This is written out as a
little-endian integer, so the 'a' byte ends up at the lowest address,
and the 'b' byte ends up at the highest address.

convert: Update drs file extension handling

Files that were previously extracted as `.bin` files are now extracted
as `.bina` files. This means those files are now treated the same way
for all game versions.

codecompliance: ignore merge-commit-dates

When a PR gets merged in another year than the commits are dated,
the expected copyright year in the changed files changes to the
merge-commits year. This makes the copyright year wrong according to our
codecompliance check.
This might happen, because of a PR gets merged in a year after the last
change, or because the PR got rebased without '--ignore-date'.

buildsystem: register generated files as byproducts

This means that these generated files are not guaranteed to exist/update.
Which is good, because then cmake will not run the codegen again and again
to try to update the files. They are not updated if their content does not change,
because that would cause project rebuilds even though there's no reason
for that rebuild (the file would just be touched).

buildsystem: fix dependency on unnecessary timefile

This caused rebuilds because the generated files depend on the first
file (see cmake sources, e.g. https://github.com/Kitware/CMake/blob/b4ccb6cd32029efa802dfdfa889c75bc16f65cf1/Source/cmMakefileTargetGenerator.cxx#L974-L1006).
The first file (the timefile) is touched after the files were generated.
The generated files are then older than the timefile, and are touched,
causing rebuils for any (non-generated) source file depending on them.

codegen: create generated files as byproducts

The CMake Makefile generator will now know how to create missing files,
but this is still better than recompiling half the project
when we just touched the root CMakeLists.txt. The reason behind this
is that CMake's make generator will touch each generated output
in order to make sure depending files get built.
CMake introduced this behavior in its codebase with commit
Kitware/CMake@66a9c90c4bb5bf93bd570a423f99486b24b9337d.

I'm not sure why CMake even does this, because if the code generator
actually updates the file, then there's no need to touch it. Otherwise
if the generated file was not updated, the depending files don't need
any rebuild on purpose.

This is an adapted revert of 51ac97d39c0b826c39070c50e1146ea1521cc6b2,
where the timefile is reintroduced, but the outputs are once again
written as BYPRODUCTS, just like we introduced in commit
0d60241d0779cb843ba8ef26af19298692482ed1 and removed again in
2fc83d7da2f4351b999d42c7bd27f7485acd9f6e.

buildsystem: no transitive linkage for internally used libraries

if the linking is declared PUBLIC, e.g. all the python modules that
link against libopenage would link to all of libopenage's dependencies
again. when one of those, e.g. libnyan.so, is updated, the module will be
linked again. this means if e.g. libnyan is updated, all python modules
are relinked. this commit removes this transitive linking, and python
modules won't be rebuilt any more.

Signed-off-by: David Heidelberg <david@ixit.cz>

Introduce flatpak build for Linux!

Flatpak uses KDE Runtime and SDK (since it has Qt libs).

Wayland has to be disabled due to https://github.com/SFTtech/openage/issues/1300

There is currently enabled too many permission, when game starts working
properly, it needs to be tightened to required minimum.

Cleanup phase should be implemented in future (for headers and other
stuff which remains after libraries).

Depend on: https://github.com/SFTtech/openage/pull/1348
Closes: https://github.com/SFTtech/openage/issues/1050

Bugfix: Correct the damage_modifier_2 bitmask

`damage_modifier_2` is 6 bits long, but the bitmask `0x1F` had only 5 bits (contrary to what the comment above it says). This PR fixes that.

This fix is also aligned with the SMX specification (https://github.com/SFTtech/openage/blob/master/doc/media/smx-files.md) in this project. I found this bug and validated the proposed fix when I was implementing my own SMX updater library in Python.
Add Jens Nyman to the list of contributors

Explicitly initialize integers created via cdef

Not doing this led (on my machine) to some weird non-deterministic behavior: In a small number of resources, the palette would vary in the first 4 pixels (4to5 compression)
